### OccurrenceDate
The exact date and time when the traffic collision occurred.  
Used to analyze temporal patterns and determine collision trends over time.

### Month
The month extracted from the occurrence date.  
Useful for seasonal trend analysis (winter vs. summer collision rates).

### Day_of_Week
Indicates which day the collision happened (Monday–Sunday).  
Helps identify weekday vs. weekend risk patterns.

### Year
The calendar year of the collision event.  
Allows long‑term trend analysis and year‑over‑year comparisons.

### Hour
The hour (0–23) during which the collision occurred.  
Critical for identifying high‑risk time periods, especially night hours.

### Neighbourhood
The Toronto neighbourhood where the collision took place.  
Enables geographic risk mapping and neighbourhood‑level safety insights.

### Fatalities
Number of deaths resulting from the collision.  
Used to measure severe accident hotspots and impact severity scoring.

### Injury_Collisions
Number of collisions that resulted in injuries.  
Indicates locations with frequent harmful incidents.

### FTR_Collisions
"Fail to Remain" (hit‑and‑run) collision count.  
Used to identify unsafe areas prone to non‑reporting or fleeing drivers.

### PD_Collisions
Property‑Damage‑Only collision count.  
Helps measure collision frequency even when injuries are not involved.
